Just a short walk east off the summit of Arthur's Seat provides this view of both the city and the face of the Salisbury Crags. Extinct volcano, rugged cliffs, and vibrant city all in one shot. If you're not walking up this hill on your visit to Edinburgh, you're missing out on something truly special.

Sunday afternoon, old graveyard not far from my flat in Edinburgh, these the bottom half of these trees were already in deep shadow - there was only about half an hour of sunlight left, dipping low, low, low in the autumn sky in the afternoon now, zoomed in on the tops of the trees which were catching those very final rays of an autumn Sunday, soft, soft honey-golden light caught on them for a few precious moments then into shadow thence into the long night...
Venus setting over the Pentlands and the old town from Calton Hill

just a few moments after I zoomed in to take the last of the light still touching the top of the trees and it was gone, shadows growing over the world, the colours fading - you can just see a tiny flare of red in between the branches of the tree in the middle of the shot here, the sun actually now below the horizon but a final flaring of copper, a last hurrah of twilight before night proper. And with that I walked out the top gate and across the road to the welcoming warm glow of the pub...

Molly, Bert and I going for an evening stroll in the Pentlands, Edinburgh. 

Boy was it windy that day. I had real difficulties walking. You can see me leaning into the wind so taking this photo was somewhat difficult. The plan was to have Molly and Bert sit next to me but as usual they had plans of their own. :-)

Spent the afternoon wandering around Cramond Island today - you can reach it on a walkway when the tide is low enough. We stayed until sunset which, as it had been such a lovely day, was pretty spectacular. This shot was taken as the sun disappeared behind the clouds - less intense but I love the contrast of the blue sky reflected on the water.
